text: I love the style of this trailer. It's not trying to be flashy or in depth with the story. It's just that gritty action vibe that was so popular in the late 80s and early 90s. This really feels like a sequel to Predator 2. Jungle to City to Suburbs. It's perfect. I'm just glad Shane Black is having fun with this. I miss the more lighthearted sequels that don't try to remove the corn factor and just go with with the pure nonsensical action. Now there are action movie franchises where you should take the story fairly seriously, but this isn't one of them. You just go to see these movies for blood, guts and explosions. This will be quite refreshing.

Now it's an elite team of human soldiers outfitted with predator tech vs. the ancient alien hunters. Midpoint: the government codebreaker learns that this isn't a normal hunting party they're fighting, this is a recon team sent to recover all the Predator tech, and if they can't collect it their objective is to blow up the entire muthafuggin planet. text: ...One of the most generic trailers I've ever seen.   This was a trailer that needed to build suspense and anticipation for the  "ultimate reveal" of the Predator,  and yet, we see him in full view within the first 5 seconds of this "teaser".   Oh, and take out "From the director of Iron Man 3" because that's doing you absolutely no favors.  My excitement for this movie has plummeted. It's one thing to have a mediocre trailer, it's another to blow your load and show the titular character so quickly, hastily pasting in obnoxious and overused orchestral effects to "hype things up" and then proceed to bombard us with a hundred split second shots without even the faintest idea of flow or coherence.

text: I, I don't know about this.  When I think predator, I think jungles and camouflage and dropping down from trees and ripping people in half. I don't think kids and toys and scrawny little dudes playing "assassin"; I miss the good old days when action heroes looked larger than life. This everyday man was John Mccain's thing. It doesn't work with every body. Those Soldiers in the first film looked like bad asses and a real challenge for the Predator. You believed that they were the best of the best when it came to the kind of solider Earth had to offer. BUT they missed this point in the other films.   I know he is used a lot in Hollywood, but The Rock vs the Predator. Now that would be a fun movie.   Mixed feelings about this trailer. It didn't look bad, but it kind of numbed the excitement I had for the film.

text: leaked script info proceed with caution Steve McKenna and his US special forces squad are in Cuba with orders to eliminate some drug lord and free the hostages. Suddenly an escape pod falls from the skies. The squad finds and unconscious Predator there and McKenna quickly expropriates helmet and weapon as evidence of an alien contact. They see a CIA chopper headin' to their location, McKenna runs away. Predator's up and kills USSF men then gets cought by CIA. McKenna mails the items to his storage cell right before gettin' cought as well. Because McKenna didn't pay for the storage the items are sent to the adress... where we meet his ex-wife and autistic son Robie. Of course little fella is a linguistic genius and bein' bullied at school. Casey (Munn's scientist character) is sent to a secret CIA base where Predator's held captive. While studying Predator's biology she learns that he was easily caught and that the base stores a lot of alien weaponry (from previous movies). Too late tho. - Meanwhile... McKenna is bein' transported to a madhouse with six other ex-soldiers via bus when guards are ordered to deliver him to the very same "secret" base for more questioning (what the hell?). They arrive just in time for the Predator's break out and McKenna uses the moment to escape. With the support of other prisoners he rescues Casey and they all make it to the chopper ("get to the chopper" line drop). Meanwhile... Robie examines the items, "hacks" them and learn alien language. This starts a chain of events which resulted in another Predator comin' to Earth (he's called "Upgrade" in the script). He's three meters tall and looks more like humna than classic Predators. He needs an those items. - McKenna & co make it to his son just in time to save him from both Predators. When Upgrade and runaway Predator first meet face to face the tall one kills the other with one blow. - Upgrade is some kind of an intergalactic assassin. His task is to kill dissident Predatorsn who are hiding on Earth in Area 52 and work for the organization which protects it from aliens (umm... seriously?). Closer to the end our heroes find Upgrade's "hidden" ship in Florida (it was stolen from him by dissident Predator). Soon the ship's owner arives, releases a bunch of hybrids (three-legged Predators, spider Predators, etc) and they go to attack Area 52 (on foot... go figure). McKenna & co fly ahead and after a brief exposition get explained that there's urgent need to bring the rest of dissident Predators to the very same ship. From there they use cars for transportation (movie logic). What to expect: Robi puts on Predator's mask / shoulder canon and decides to walk the the streets in the midst of Halloween. He stumbles on school bullies, one of them throws an apple at him which Predator tech automatically perceive as an attack.. with corresponding consequences. Yes, it's a Halloween movie instead of Black's usual Christmas Eve. More Predator dogs. One of them gets an "accidental lobotomy", becomes friendly, helps the heroes and overall very cute (because we gotta sell toys). Obligatory "Robie drivin' the alien ship" scenes. Predator is forced to use a machine gun (AvP movie reference). Lots of references, line drops and easter eggs. Predators actually take spinal cord to collect human DNA and inject it into themselves in order to become stronger (because hunting trophies is sooo last century, right?) There's a Dutch cameo but the scene can be easy cut from the story and the character can be easily replaced with Glover's or Baldwin's characters from P2. this is going to be so bad

No sunshine.  No kids.  No elementary schools.  No suburbs. No love story.  Use legit larger than life actors that compete on and off screen.  The Alien and Predator movies have drifted far off course.  Let's bring it home.  Also, stop trying to build some type of myth, from we we worshipped them (AvP) to this hybridization crap. text: I'm pretty sure that basing movies (especially remakes and sequels) on pop culture characters is just asking for trouble. All these massively popular characters - Han Solo, Aliens, Superman, the Predator, Mary Poppins (just a few) - build up such a fanbase that the movies are incredibly hard-pressed to deliver; most of the time, that isn't going to happen. These movies collapse under the weight of the titular character's own fame and the unattainably legendary status that goes with it.

text: This trailer for the new Predator movie confirms the suspicions that Mr. Black and 20th Century Fox either forgot or chose to ignore time tested principles of success. First, true innovation is very hard and  the byproduct of luck much more than talent or skill. Creative IMITATION of successful theme or meme  is much more likely to succeed than innovation.   Mr. Black despite his directorial chops and being an uncredited co-writer of the original Predator movie,  should not have presumed to do a "reset" of the franchise.  When you re attempting to follow up the success of  prior legend the initial question should be what made the original Predator film a classic which retains old fans and attracts new ones thirty years  after its release in 1989?  It wasn't complicated plot devices or pandering to generational changes.

Everything changes however once a predator shows up again, this time out for Dutch personally since he managed to kill one of their kind and his skull (and spine) therefore makes for a highly regarded trophy. text: So theres two sides in all these comments. Intense hate. Or intense hype. And mostly its for silly reasons, especially regarding a teaser. Just relax, at worst be apprehensive. We already know the idea behind the originals will be changed somehow, but how extreme it is we wont know for awhile. Heres two examples. TMNT. Long standing fanbase going back decades, each new addition brought something new and sure there were a few flops but all in all they stayed close and true to the original. And then Michael Bay got it and most of us can agree it made lot of fans unhappy. Then youve got Fast and Furious. Where the first few were about cars, some criminal activity, races and a bond of family. The last few were basically just action movies with cool cars and tech. And hardly anyone was displeased with them. Its too early to tell but honestly ive got high hopes for it, cant wait to see where it goes. Just give it time

text: Why is it so hard to make one of these good?   Here‚Äôs what the fans want:  A plot that focuses on the Predator(s) as an anti-hero.  Show the audience the Yautja‚Äôs with more depth than silent invisible killing machines and have them interacting with their own people.  What makes them tick? What is their world like. Do they all hunt for sport? Obviously not considering a lot of them must be at home developing all this weaponry and tech.    There is so much that could be done to raise the bar on this franchise, but instead of investing in a great story filmmakers just churn out the same piece of junk with different characters getting killed off with one of them making it to the end who survives.  Its old and mundane.    Yautja‚Äôs are an ancient and civilized society with a code of honor. The franchise deserves a movie that delves into the substance of their species and provide some awesome back story to the 30 years of movies we‚Äôve been watching.

text: There won't be another Predator movie as good as the first one. There are many reasons for this, like the fact that the original cast was amazing. But the main fact is that, in the first one, you don't  know what was hiding and chasing them in the jungle. This feeling of mystery and suspense is lost forever, beacause we already know how the monster looks and what it's capable of. Now, add a poor and unoriginal plot, replace the suspense with some comedy and jokes, remove the masculinity and replace it with female warriors and kids, and then you'll have a trashy movie like this one (in my opinion) will be. In summary: Predator 1987: A goddamn sexual Tyrannosaurus. Predator 2018: The CIA got you pushing too many pencils.

text: Okay the Yautja would never genetically alter themselves with other species they are a pure tribal race of blooded Warriors that would view any such hybridisation as an abomination. Why do you think scar was sent to take out the predalien in AVP requiem?  It saw what happened to its Fallen Brother as a defilement that needed to be cleansed away. Total rubbish. Is this movie going to fit in with 2010s predators in any way shape or form? Are we going to hear back from  Royce or Isabel? Did  they survive the game preserve planet? Did they get back to Earth? And I'm aware of the comic book strip of what happened after the movie so I'm aware they stayed on the planet in the comics but that does not necessarily mean they will continue off that continuity. I would very much appreciate seeing those two characters back in this movie to the two together. Are we going to have any references or cameos of  Dutch or Danny Glover's character Harrigan from predator 2? The trailer didn't really do much for me, it did not have any sense of fear or dread and it looked  PG-13, isn't it supposed to be rated R? This plot point about the Yautja genetically changing themselves really is stupid. This trailer really shows nothing hopefully it's not a sign of things to come I really want this movie to be good, I have been waiting decades for a proper Predator sequel.

text: The film looks to be just like every other film made in the 2010s. A Politically Correct and generic product where statistics and marketing are the only important thing. When they announced that Shane Black was involved and that Thomas Jane had been cast, my hope started rising. I thought maybe this could bring some of the good old days of action back, I couldn't be more wrong.  Thomas Jane has something that very few people have: He can be as badass as he wants and he CAN ACT, this is very rare in modern actors. I am sure that a film with that 'isolation' feeling everyone is talking about could have worked outstandingly well with just Thomas Jane and the Predator. They are wasting such a professional with the supporting role they gave him.

text: I thought for a minute when the lady said "they are attempting hybridisation", I was almost excited they were trying for the Concrete Jungle story (a hidden gem video game from 2005). However, then she clarified the "they" as being the Predators and now I'm certain the movie will be garbage.  I mean, why do the Predators suddenly need some new motivation other than their honour-driven trophy hunting? It's literally the underlying foundation of all the Predator movies, even the garbage AvP ones. It was what made the Predator character unique. Now, they are going to be just another alien invader bent on annihilation, domination, or assimilation. Such a tired trope.

text: Looks awesome. I hate that everyone is against the fact that it's different from the original. The original was good but we already saw that movie, why watch it again? And if you do want to watch it again then just watch it again. It's not like anyone's stopping you. I personally think it looks cool. I like the idea of it being more action based too because we've gotten more scary movies from predator than action movies and when they did try to do action movies with it in that past it didn't work very great so I'm glad this one looks like it might do that right. Also, Jacob Trembley is always a win. I also see a lot of complaints about "from the director of iron man 3". Just because a director makes one movie that's meh doesn't mean they can't make something really good too. Just look at Stephen Spielberg, Tim Burton, and John Hughs. They've all made a lot of really good movies and a few poor ones too so whos to say that this director can't make up for Iron man 3. The movie might be really good, which I think it will be, or it might be really bad, or it might just be okay. Fact is if it's bad you can still watch the old one and if it's good then we can all enjoy it. So don't complain untill you see the movie. Just sit back and hope for the best.

text: The amount of hate this is already getting is disappointing. I for one think this will be an amazing film. I'm a huge fan of the Predator films, and I've enjoyed every movie. Can't wait to see this one!! I think the idea of them genetically upgrading themselves is phenomenal! In my opinion, it adds more to the film, not just focusing on fear alone. Let's just hope this film won't receive so much hate because people are a little salty about wanting to keep the feeling of the original. I get wanting to go back to old times, I watch the first film as much as I can I adore it, but, I think the change in the movies is good! It's good to see these lethal hunters get smarter, and better over time. Many argue that the films are focusing more on the characters than the Predators. Now yes, they have done that, but it's supposed to pull you in, make you like the characters before they're quite possibly killed, giving you a good scare. Please do keep in mind, ALL OF THIS IS MY OPINION! I just hope we can appreciate the film for what it is, and not criticize it for what it's not.

text: The Predators are back on Earth with a new mission in the first trailer for The Predator. Arnold Schwarzenegger and John McTiernan launched the alien fighting franchise back in 1987, but what has followed failed to live up to the first installment. In an effort to revitalize the IP once more, Fox turned to writer/director Shane Black. Although he's best known for his work behind the camera, Black has major ties to the franchise already since he played Hawkins in Predator.  Black channeled his love for the franchise to create a reboot that still serves as a sequel to the events of the previous films. He assembled a great cast for his take too. Jacob Tremblay, Boyd Holbrook, Sterling K. Brown, Trevante Rhodes, Olivia Munn, and more are all set to appear, and we finally get to know what this movie is. text: Alright, just saw the movie tonight. AVOID AT ALL COSTS It's terrible. Awful. Worse than Predators, and that's hard to do. The CGI looks worse than it did in AVP, which is shocking.  They made fun of mental disorders throughout the ENTIRE movie. A few jokes of that sort are fine, and don't bother me, but they did it the ENTIRE film.  They tried too hard to be like the original, as well. Butchered lines from the original, tried to re-crate the "rag tag" band of soldiers, but horribly failed. I'd say the worst offender in this movie, by far, is how awful the effects were. I seriously don't think they were finished with them, but had to release the film. The blood has a weird 3D CGI look to it, both the human, and predator blood. The ships looked pretty bad, and the predators themselves looked pretty bad with their masks off.  Do NOT waste your time or money with this film. If you REALLY want to see it, wait until it comes out on streaming.
